22. Kh1 Bd6 23. Bf5 Rcd8 {(Krasenkow)} 24. Bd4 Qxc2 25. Bxc2 Nxd5 {
almost equalises.}) 20. exd5 Bxb2 $1 {Black has regained his pawn.} 21. d6 $1 {
White starts an attack in the centre.} Qc6 22. f3 Rec8 23. Bh7+ $1 Kh8 24. Be4
Qxc5+ 25. Qxc5 Rxc5 26. Bxb7 {
Topalov has a dangerous passed pawn in the endgame.} Rd8 27. Rfe1 Be5 $6 ({
Better is} 27... Re5 $5 28. Rxe5 Bxe5 29. d7 {but White wins probably.}) 28. d7
a5 29. f4 Bc7 30. Bd5 $1 Kh7 31. Bxf7 Rf5 32. Ba2 Rxf4 33. Bb1+ Kg8 34. Bg6 $1
Bb6+ 35. Kh1 Bc5 36. Rc1 $6 (36. Re8+ $1 Rf8 37. Rd3 $1 {ends the game.}) 36...
Bf8 37. Red1 Bxa3 $6 (37... Rc4 {tries to survive.}) 38. Rc8 Rff8 39. Be8 Be7
40. Re1 Bg5 41. g3 a4 42. h4 Bf6 43. Re6 $1 {White threatens 44.Rxf6! Topalov
had won the game, event and 150,000 euro.   The final standings in the
Bilbao-score became: Topalov 17, Aronian and Carlsen 13, Ivanchuk 12, Radjabov
10 and Anand 8. The traditional scores were: Topalov 61/2/10, Aronian, Carlsen
and Ivanchuk 5, Radjabov 41/2, Anand 4.} 1-0

